ts slogans, names, phrase, logo, and symbol, renewed forever-every 10 years, must renew in between 5th and 6th year.Illegal Useof a celebrities name/image.MonopolyMarket control by one firm. (local cable systems)MonopsonyMarket with one buyer or one employer. Professional athletics; in other countries it is leagues in football.DuopolyMarket control by two firms, OC/LA: Dodgers and Angels.OligopolyMarket is controlled by a handful of firms. Movie theaters, hotels, movie studios, music labels, theme parks.Perfect CompetitionNo market control- lots of firms- identical products (perfect substitutes). If they utilize brand they are not perfect competition.Monopolistic CompetitionNo Market control- lots of firms- slightly different products (utilize branding, advertising, or quality(real or not)- to create differences).Lots of Government ControlState-run-controls the type of contentAnti-Trustoutlawed trusts (avoid collusion between companies)Excessive Market Controlbarriers of entry too high for a new company.Little Government ControlDeregulation, and minimal amount of companies control mediaCollusiontwo companies or more within same industry collaborate to get competitor out of business.Trade OrganizationsMPAA- FilmNAB-Radio, TVESA- Video GamesEMA- Home EntertainmentABA- BookAAAA- AdvertisingTIES- ECO- TourismTrade Associations Duties2. Public Relations Tool- Rate Content on movies,looking out for families Self- Regulate-way of keeping government out.Advertise- often an ethical appeal.ethical appeal, hurting the people behind the scenes.Prior to copyright act of 1976copyrights lasted 28-95 yearsPublic Domainno copyright or copyright expired.Grants"exclusive rights" copyright holders (they are the only ones that can make money off of their content)Codified/fair useeducational purposes; you can use copyrighted property for educational purposes.Protect Intellectual PropertyCreations of the mind;Defined "works of authorship" - literary works, musical works+ words, films.Medi